I think these issues in tests should be fixed. The tests should not depend on each other.

**JUnit won't guarantee the execution order** of the tests as it says: 
Tests can use the objects (variables) in a test fixture, with each test invoking different methods on objects in the fixture and asserting different expected results. Each test runs in its own test fixture to isolate tests from the changes made by other tests. That is, tests don't share the state of objects in the test fixture. **`Because the tests are isolated, they can be run in any order`**. (refer to [this](http://junit.sourceforge.net/doc/faq/faq.htm#tests_2))
